[
    {
        "content": "<p>In <a href=\"https://youtu.be/5phJVSWdWg4?t=2230\">https://youtu.be/5phJVSWdWg4?t=2230</a> , <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"275920\">@John Baez</span> says that the only role of the continuity condition is to rule out nonobvious solutions to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>ϕ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>m</mi><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>ϕ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>m</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>+</mo><mi>ϕ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\phi(mn)=\\phi(m)+\\phi(n)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">ϕ</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">mn</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">ϕ</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">m</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">ϕ</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>. Equivalently we can define <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>ψ</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>ϕ</mi><mo>∘</mo><mi>exp</mi><mo>⁡</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> \\psi = \\phi \\circ \\exp </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">ψ</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">ϕ</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∘</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\">exp</span></span></span></span> and rule out nonobvious solutions to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>ψ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>m</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>ψ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>m</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>+</mo><mi>ψ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\psi(m+n)=\\psi(m)+\\psi(n)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">ψ</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">m</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">ψ</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">m</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">ψ</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>ψ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>m</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\psi(m)&gt;0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">ψ</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">m</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">&gt;</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span></span></span></span>. Surely we should get that by requiring <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>ψ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>a</mi><mi>m</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><mi>ψ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>m</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\psi(am)=a\\psi(m)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">ψ</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">am</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">ψ</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">m</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> for all <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">a&gt;0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5782em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">&gt;</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span></span></span></span>. Instead of \"convex\" we would say \"conical\", instead of probability measures we would have measures. Right?</p>\n<div class=\"youtube-video message_inline_image\"><a data-id=\"5phJVSWdWg4\" href=\"https://youtu.be/5phJVSWdWg4?t=2230\"><img src=\"https://uploads.zulipusercontent.net/ea9e7b1c2b0adef4922cd31c849dec604e9602b5/68747470733a2f2f692e7974696d672e636f6d2f76692f3570684a565357645767342f64656661756c742e6a7067\"></a></div>",
        "id": 304835836,
        "sender_full_name": "Gurkenglas",
        "timestamp": 1666125233
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, I guess people find that starting with a function <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>ψ</mi><mo>:</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\psi  : \\mathbb{R} \\to \\mathbb{R}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">ψ</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span></span></span></span> and using the axiom <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>ψ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>a</mi><mi>m</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><mi>ψ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>m</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\psi(am) = a \\psi(m)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">ψ</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">am</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">ψ</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">m</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> to deduce that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>ψ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>m</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>c</mi><mi>m</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\psi(m) = c m </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">ψ</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">m</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">c</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">m</span></span></span></span> for some constant <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>c</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">c</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">c</span></span></span></span> is \"too easy to be interesting\": you just take <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>ψ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">c = \\psi(1)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">c</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">ψ</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> and it's obvious.</p>",
        "id": 304890549,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1666162648
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm not sure why you say \"instead of probability measures we have measures\", though.</p>",
        "id": 304890605,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1666162678
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Because when you allow not just convex combinations but conical ones, aka remove the constraint that the coefficients of a combination sum to 1, then you get all the positive multiples of each probability distribution, which are all the measures. Uh, all the finite measures, once we go beyond FinSet.</p>",
        "id": 305045849,
        "sender_full_name": "Gurkenglas",
        "timestamp": 1666215155
    }
]